06188nam a22007815i 9789633866276DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338662767 a10.1515/97896338662762doi  a(DE-B1597)637794  a(OCoLC)1393656684  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aDK189.7b.I47 2023 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a325/.347223/eng/2023081100aImperial Designs, Postimperial Extremes :bStudies in Interdisciplinary and Comparative History of Russia and Eastern Europe /ced. by Victor Taki, Andrei Cusco. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tIntroduction: The Rieber Momentum in Historiography -- tChapter 1 Forests, Navies, and Entangled Empires: Timber Export and Territorial Governance in Russia in the Eighteenth to Early Nineteenth Century -- tChapter 2 The Projects of Cossack Reform in the Russian Empire (1810s–1840s): Unification versus Flexibility -- tChapter 3 The Russian Army and the Ottoman Empire: Military Reform and Eastern Crisis -- tChapter 4 Wartime Mobilization of Ethnicity, Shifting Loyalties, and Population Politics in the Borderlands of Nationalizing Empires: Reshaping Bessarabia and Bukovina, 1914–1919 -- tChapter 5 Painting Dogs into Racoons: Entertainment and Culture in the Gulag -- tChapter 6 The Jewish Exodus to the Balkans, 1933–1938 -- tChapter 7 Weathering the Storm, Toppled by the Storm: North Korea’s Non-Transition Compared with the Transition of Romania and Albania, 1989–1991 -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnchored in the Russian Empire, but not limited to it, the eight studies in this volume explore the nineteenth-century imperial responses to the challenge of modernity, the dramatic disruptions of World War I, the radical scenarios of the interwar period and post-communist endgames at the different edges of Eurasia. The book continues and amplifies the historiographic momentum created by Alfred J. Rieber’s long and fruitful scholarly career. First, the volume addresses the attempts of Russian imperial rulers and elites to overcome the economic backwardness of the empire with respect to the West. The ensuing rivalry of several interest groups (entrepreneurs, engineers, economists) created new social forms in the subsequent rounds of modernization. The studies explore the dynamics of the metamorphoses of what Rieber famously conceptualized as a “sedimentary society” in the pre-revolutionary and early Soviet settings. Second, the volume also expands and dwells on the concept of frontier zones as dynamic, mutable, shifting areas, characterized by multi-ethnicity, religious diversity, unstable loyalties, overlapping and contradictory models of governance, and an uneasy balance between peaceful co-existence and bloody military clashes. In this connection, studies pay special attention to forced and spontaneous migrations, and population politics in modern Eurasia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBorderlandszRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismzRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aTerritory, NationalzRussiaxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aBorderlands.  aComparative history.  aEmpire.  aEurasia.  aModernity.1 aAleksov, Bojan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCusco, Andrei, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCușco, Andrei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErmolaeva, Oksana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoskut